ersities, and governments, makes a clear and compelling practical case for diversity and inclusion. He presents overwhelming evidence that teams that include different kinds of thinkers outperform homogenous groups on complex tasks, producing what he calls “diversity bonuses.” These bonuses include improved problem solving, increased innovation, and more accurate predictions—all of which lead to better results. Drawing on research in economics, psychology, computer science, and many other fields, The Diversity Bonus also tells the stories of businesses and organizations that have tapped the power of diversity to solve complex problems. The result changes the way we think about diversity at work—and far beyond.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aDiversity in the workplace. 0aKnowledge economy. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Organizational Behavior.2bisacsh  aAccuracy and precision.  aAdvertising.  aAffirmative action.  aAfrican Americans.  aAmericans.  aAnalogy.  aAnalytics.  aAsian Americans.  aAsset management.  aBiology.  aBoard of directors.  aBoeing.  aBusiness case.  aCalculation.  aCareer.  aCategorization.  aCausality.  aClassroom.  aCollaboration.  aCollective intelligence.  aCompetition.  aComputer scientist.  aCross-functional team.  aCustomer.  aDecision-making.  aDemography.  aEconomist.  aEffectiveness.  aEmpirical evidence.  aEmployment.  aEngineering.  aEnsemble learning.  aEntrepreneurship.  aEstimation.  aExplanation.  aFinding.  aFluid and crystallized intelligence.  aForecasting.  aFortune 500.  aGender diversity.  aGrutter v. Bollinger.  aHarvard University.  aHeuristic.  aHidden Figures.  aHuman resources.  aIncome.  aInference.  aInstitution.  aIntelligence analysis.  aIntersectionality.  aKnowledge ba